    "body": "The actual yellow-paper is here: https://ethereum.github.io/yellowpaper/paper.pdf \r\nAfaik, there's no definition there about the vailidity of future blocks, or how timestamps should be verified. \r\nThe 15s is the agreed-upon by node-implementors practical limit. If the block exceeeds this, then it will not be rejected per se, but just not imported right now -- it will be re-evaluated later on. \r\n\r\nWhy is this? See https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/pull/23761#discussion_r738785512 for some more info\r\n\r\n> Currently, we have no strict (consensus) requirement about time. It's just a de-facto implementation choice, that the consensus engine will soft-reject headers too far in the future. Soft, in the sense that they're kept and attempted again later.\r\n>\r\n> One funky attack: if I can set the timestamp to whatever, then I can set it close to maxuint64, or max bigint, or whatever, and effectively halt ethereum, since nobody can mine a block with a timestamp exceeding mine. More effective probably, would be to not do that, but do it so a few thousand blocks can be mined on top of mine => more havoc. ",
